            "image": "shopify://shop_images/Region_Liguria.png",
            "wineries": [
              "baia-del-sole"
            ],
            "description": "<p>Liguria is the sheer willpower of Italian winemaking, a narrow crescent where vines cling to gravity-defying terraces carved into vertical sea cliffs.</p><p>Known for \"heroic viticulture,\" this rugged coastline requires growers to maintain ancient dry-stone walls (the \"muretti a secco\") and harvest entirely by hand, often using miniature monorails to navigate slopes far too steep for machinery. The terroir is a dramatic intersection of the Alps and the Mediterranean, where soils of shattered limestone, blue clay, and crumbly slate impart a profound minerality to the wine.</p><p>This geology, combined with the constant salt-laden sea spray and the aromatic influence of the macchia (wild thyme and rosemary) defines the saline, wind-swept character of whites like Vermentino and the savory Pigato. In the east, the rare, honeyed Sciacchetrà remains a legendary nectar of the Cinque Terre, while in the west, the elegant Rossese di Dolceacqua offers a peppery, silky red that thrives in the high-altitude, sun-drenched marl.</p><p>Today, the region remains a tapestry of small-scale artisans who act as stewards of this fragile ecosystem, producing wines that serve as a liquid testament to the friction between the mountain and the sea.</p>"
          }
        },
